I also notice this meshes neatly with your Pantheon’s layered architecture:

* Semantic LiDAR senses the terrain.
* Scout traverses it.
* Rangefinder estimates distance.
* Atlas stores the map.
* Adaptive Resolution changes zoom.
* Navigator chooses the mode of travel.
* Future-Lens Reconstruction lets you navigate from hypothetical future landmarks back toward the present.

That gives the Pantheon not just a map, but a meta-navigation system that decides how to reason based on the terrain rather than assuming one reasoning style fits every problem.